@c    THE BOOK OF GENESIS



@c    This book is so called from its treating of the GENERATION, that is, of
@c    the creation and the beginning of the world.  The Hebrews call it
@c    BERESITH, from the Word with which it begins.  It contains not only the
@c    history of the Creation of the world; but also an account of its
@c    progress during the space of 2369 years, that is, until the death of
@c    JOSEPH.



@c    Genesis Chapter 1


@c    God createth Heaven and Earth, and all things therein, in six days.

@c    1:1. In the beginning God created heaven, and earth.

@c    1:2. And the earth was void and empty, and darkness was upon the face
@c    of the deep; and the spirit of God moved over the waters.

@c    1:3. And God said:  Be light made.  And light was made.

@c    1:4. And God saw the light that it was good; and he divided the light
@c    from the darkness.

@c    1:5. And he called the light Day, and the darkness Night; and there was
@c    evening and morning one day.

@c    1:6. And God said:  Let there be a firmament made amidst the waters:  and
@c    let it divide the waters from the waters.

@c    A firmament. . .By this name is here understood the whole space between
@c    the earth, and the highest stars.  The lower part of which divideth the
@c    waters that are upon the earth, from those that are above in the
@c    clouds.

@c    1:7. And God made a firmament, and divided the waters that were under
@c    the firmament, from those that were above the firmament, and it was so.

@c    1:8. And God called the firmament, Heaven; and the evening and morning
@c    were the second day.

@c    1:9. God also said; Let the waters that are under the heaven, be
@c    gathered together into one place:  and let the dry land appear.  And it
@c    was so done.

@c    1:10. And God called the dry land, Earth; and the gathering together of
@c    the waters, he called Seas.  And God saw that it was good.

@c    1:11. And he said:  let the earth bring forth green herb, and such as
@c    may seed, and the fruit tree yielding fruit after its kind, which may
@c    have seed in itself upon the earth.  And it was so done.

@c    1:12. And the earth brought forth the green herb, and such as yieldeth
@c    seed according to its kind, and the tree that beareth fruit, having
@c    seed each one according to its kind.  And God saw that it was good.

@c    1:13. And the evening and the morning were the third day.

@c    1:14. And God said:  Let there be lights made in the firmament of
@c    heaven, to divide the day and the night, and let them be for signs, and
@c    for seasons, and for days and years:

@c    1:15. To shine in the firmament of heaven, and to give light upon the
@c    earth, and it was so done.

@c    1:16. And God made two great lights:  a greater light to rule the day;
@c    and a lesser light to rule the night:  and the stars.

@c    Two great lights. . .God created on the first day, light, which being
@c    moved from east to west, by its rising and setting, made morning and
@c    evening.  But on the fourth day he ordered and distributed this light,
@c    and made the sun, moon, and stars.  The moon, though much less than the
@c    stars, is here called a great light, from its giving a far greater
@c    light to the earth than any of them.

@c    1:17. And he set them in the firmament of heaven to shine upon the
@c    earth.

@c    1:18. And to rule the day and the night, and to divide the light and
@c    the darkness.  And God saw that it was good.

@c    1:19. And the evening and morning were the fourth day.

@c    1:20. God also said:  let the waters bring forth the creeping creature
@c    having life, and the fowl that may fly over the earth under the
@c    firmament of heaven.

@c    1:21. And God created the great whales, and every living and moving
@c    creature, which the waters brought forth, according to their kinds, and
@c    every winged fowl according to its kind.  And God saw that it was good.

@c    1:22. And he blessed them, saying:  Increase and multiply, and fill the
@c    waters of the sea:  and let the birds be multiplied upon the earth.

@c    1:23. And the evening and morning were the fifth day.

@c    1:24. And God said:  Let the earth bring forth the living creature in
@c    its kind, cattle and creeping things, and beasts of the earth,
@c    according to their kinds.  And it was so done.

@c    1:25. And God made the beasts of the earth according to their kinds,
@c    and cattle, and every thing that creepeth on the earth after its kind.
@c    And God saw that it was good.

@c    1:26. And he said:  Let us make man to our image and likeness:  and let
@c    him have dominion over the fishes of the sea, and the fowls of the air,
@c    and the beasts, and the whole earth, and every creeping creature that
@c    moveth upon the earth.

@c    Let us make man to our image. . .This image of God in man, is not in the
@c    body, but in the soul; which is a spiritual substance, endued with
@c    understanding and free will.  God speaketh here in the plural number, to
@c    insinuate the plurality of persons in the Deity.

@c    1:27. And God created man to his own image:  to the image of God he
@c    created him:  male and female he created them.

@c    1:28. And God blessed them, saying:  Increase and multiply, and fill the
@c    earth, and subdue it, and rule over the fishes of the sea, and the
@c    fowls of the air, and all living creatures that move upon the earth.

@c    Increase and multiply. . .This is not a precept, as some Protestant
@c    controvertists would have it, but a blessing, rendering them fruitful;
@c    for God had said the same words to the fishes, and birds, (ver. 22) who
@c    were incapable of receiving a precept.

@c    1:29. And God said:  Behold I have given you every herb bearing seed
@c    upon the earth, and all trees that have in themselves seed of their own
@c    kind, to be your meat:

@c    1:30. And to all beasts of the earth, and to every fowl of the air, and
@c    to all that move upon the earth, and wherein there is life, that they
@c    may have to feed upon.  And it was so done.

@c    1:31. And God saw all the things that he had made, and they were very
@c    good.  And the evening and morning were the sixth day.



@c    Genesis Chapter 2


@c    God resteth on the seventh day and blesseth it.  The earthly paradise,
@c    in which God placeth man.  He commandeth him not to eat of the tree of
@c    knowledge.  And formeth a woman of his rib.

@c    2:1. So the heavens and the earth were finished, and all the furniture
@c    of them.

@c    2:2. And on the seventh day God ended his work which he had made:  and
@c    he rested on the seventh day from all his work which he had done.

@c    He rested, etc. . .That is, he ceased to make or create any new kinds of
@c    things.  Though, as our Lord tells us, John 5.17, "He still worketh",
@c    viz., by conserving and governing all things, and creating souls.

@c    2:3. And he blessed the seventh day, and sanctified it:  because in it
@c    he had rested from all his work which God created and made.

@c    2:4. These are the generations of the heaven and the earth, when they
@c    were created, in the day that the Lord God made the heaven and the
@c    earth:

@c    2:5. And every plant of the field before it sprung up in the earth, and
@c    every herb of the ground before it grew:  for the Lord God had not
@c    rained upon the earth; and there was not a man to till the earth.

@c    2:6. But a spring rose out of the earth, watering all the surface of
@c    the earth.

@c    2:7. And the Lord God formed man of the slime of the earth:  and
@c    breathed into his face the breath of life, and man became a living
@c    soul.

@c    2:8. And the Lord God had planted a paradise of pleasure from the
@c    beginning:  wherein he placed man whom he had formed.

@c    2:9. And the Lord God brought forth of the ground all manner of trees,
@c    fair to behold, and pleasant to eat of:  the tree of life also in the
@c    midst of paradise:  and the tree of knowledge of good and evil.

@c    The tree of life. . .So called because it had that quality, that by
@c    eating of the fruit of it, man would have been preserved in a constant
@c    state of health, vigour, and strength, and would not have died at all.
@c    The tree of knowledge. . .To which the deceitful serpent falsely
@c    attributed the power of imparting a superior kind of knowledge, beyond
@c    that which God was pleased to give.

@c    2:10. And a river went out of the place of pleasure to water paradise,
@c    which from thence is divided into four heads.

@c    2:11. The name of the one is Phison:  that is it which compasseth all
@c    the land of Hevilath, where gold groweth.

@c    2:12. And the gold of that land is very good:  there is found bdellium,
@c    and the onyx stone.

@c    2:13. And the name of the second river is Gehon:  the same is it that
@c    compasseth all the land of Ethiopia.

@c    2:14. And the name of the third river is Tigris:  the same passeth along
@c    by the Assyrians.  And the fourth river is Euphrates.

@c    2:15. And the Lord God took man, and put him into the paradise of
@c    pleasure, to dress it, and to keep it.

@c    2:16. And he commanded him, saying:  Of every tree of paradise thou
@c    shalt eat:

@c    2:17. But of the tree of knowledge of good and evil, thou shalt not
@c    eat.  For in what day soever thou shalt eat of it, thou shalt die the
@c    death.

@c    2:18. And the Lord God said:  It is not good for man to be alone:  let us
@c    make him a help like unto himself.

@c    2:19. And the Lord God having formed out of the ground all the beasts
@c    of the earth, and all the fowls of the air, brought them to Adam to see
@c    what he would call them:  for whatsoever Adam called any living creature
@c    the same is its name.

@c    2:20. And Adam called all the beasts by their names, and all the fowls
@c    of the air, and all the cattle of the field:  but for Adam there was not
@c    found a helper like himself.

@c    2:21. Then the Lord God cast a deep sleep upon Adam:  and when he was
@c    fast asleep, he took one of his ribs, and filled up flesh for it.

@c    2:22. And the Lord God built the rib which he took from Adam into a
@c    woman:  and brought her to Adam.

@c    2:23. And Adam said:  This now is bone of my bones, and flesh of my
@c    flesh; she shall be called woman, because she was taken out of man.

@c    2:24. Wherefore a man shall leave father and mother, and shall cleave
@c    to his wife:  and they shall be two in one flesh.

@c    2:25. And they were both naked:  to wit, Adam and his wife:  and were not
@c    ashamed.



@c    Genesis Chapter 3


@c    The serpent's craft.  The fall of our first parents.  Their punishment.
@c    The promise of a Redeemer.

@c    3:1. Now the serpent was more subtle than any of the beasts of the
@c    earth which the Lord God had made.  And he said to the woman:  Why hath
@c    God commanded you, that you should not eat of every tree of paradise?

@c    3:2. And the woman answered him, saying:  Of the fruit of the trees that
@c    are in paradise we do eat:

@c    3:3. But of the fruit of the tree which is in the midst of paradise,
@c    God hath commanded us that we should not eat; and that we should not
@c    touch it, lest perhaps we die.

@c    3:4. And the serpent said to the woman:  No, you shall not die the
@c    death.

@c    3:5. For God doth know that in what day soever you shall eat thereof,
@c    your eyes shall be opened:  and you shall be as Gods, knowing good and
@c    evil.

@c    3:6. And the woman saw that the tree was good to eat, and fair to the
@c    eyes, and delightful to behold:  and she took of the fruit thereof, and
@c    did eat, and gave to her husband, who did eat.

@c    3:7. And the eyes of them both were opened:  and when they perceived
@c    themselves to be naked, they sewed together fig leaves, and made
@c    themselves aprons.

@c    And the eyes, etc. . .Not that they were blind before, (for the woman
@c    saw that the tree was fair to the eyes, ver. 6.) nor yet that their
@c    eyes were opened to any more perfect knowledge of good; but only to the
@c    unhappy experience of having lost the good of original grace and
@c    innocence, and incurred the dreadful evil of sin.  From whence followed
@c    a shame of their being naked; which they minded not before; because
@c    being now stript of original grace, they quickly began to be subject to
@c    the shameful rebellions of the flesh.

@c    3:8. And when they heard the voice of the Lord God walking in paradise
@c    at the afternoon air, Adam and his wife hid themselves from the face of
@c    the Lord God, amidst the trees of paradise.

@c    3:9. And the Lord God called Adam, and said to him:  Where art thou?

@c    3:10. And he said:  I heard thy voice in paradise; and I was afraid,
@c    because I was naked, and I hid myself.

@c    3:11. And he said to him:  And who hath told thee that thou wast naked,
@c    but that thou hast eaten of the tree whereof I commanded thee that thou
@c    shouldst not eat?

@c    3:12. And Adam said:  The woman, whom thou gavest me to be my companion,
@c    gave me of the tree, and I did eat.

@c    3:13. And the Lord God said to the woman:  Why hast thou done this?  And
@c    she answered:  The serpent deceived me, and I did eat.

@c    3:14. And the Lord God said to the serpent:  Because thou hast done this
@c    thing, thou art cursed among all cattle, and beasts of the earth:  upon
@c    thy breast shalt thou go, and earth shalt thou eat all the days of thy
@c    life.

@c    3:15. I will put enmities between thee and the woman, and thy seed and
@c    her seed:  she shall crush thy head, and thou shalt lie in wait for her
@c    heel.

@c    She shall crush. . .Ipsa, the woman; so divers of the fathers read this
@c    place, conformably to the Latin:  others read it ipsum, viz., the seed.
@c    The sense is the same:  for it is by her seed, Jesus Christ, that the
@c    woman crushes the serpent's head.

@c    3:16. To the woman also he said:  I will multiply thy sorrows, and thy
@c    conceptions:  in sorrow shalt thou bring forth children, and thou shalt
@c    be under thy husband's power, and he shall have dominion over thee.

@c    3:17. And to Adam he said:  Because thou hast hearkened to the voice of
@c    thy wife, and hast eaten of the tree, whereof I commanded thee, that
@c    thou shouldst not eat, cursed is the earth in thy work:  with labour and
@c    toil shalt thou eat thereof all the days of thy life.

@c    3:18. Thorns and thistles shall it bring forth to thee, and thou shalt
@c    eat the herbs of the earth.

@c    3:19. In the sweat of thy face shalt thou eat bread till thou return to
@c    the earth out of which thou wast taken:  for dust thou art, and into
@c    dust thou shalt return.

@c    3:20. And Adam called the name of his wife Eve:  because she was the
@c    mother of all the living.

@c    3:21. And the Lord God made for Adam and his wife garments of skins,
@c    and clothed them.

@c    3:22. And he said:  Behold Adam is become as one of us, knowing good and
@c    evil:  now therefore lest perhaps he put forth his hand and take also of
@c    the tree of life, and eat, and live for ever.

@c    Behold Adam, etc. . .This was spoken by way of reproaching him with his
@c    pride, in affecting a knowledge that might make him like to God.

@c    3:23. And the Lord God sent him out of the paradise of pleasure, to
@c    till the earth from which he was taken.

@c    3:24. And he cast out Adam:  and placed before the paradise of pleasure
@c    Cherubims, and a flaming sword, turning every way, to keep the way of
@c    the tree of life.



@c    Genesis Chapter 4


@c    The history of Cain and Abel.

@c    4:1. And Adam knew Eve his wife; who conceived and brought forth Cain,
@c    saying:  I have gotten a man through God.

@c    4:2. And again she brought forth his brother Abel.  And Abel was a
@c    shepherd, and Cain a husbandman.

@c    4:3. And it came to pass after many days, that Cain offered, of the
@c    fruits of the earth, gifts to the Lord.

@c    4:4. Abel also offered of the firstlings of his flock, and of their
@c    fat:  and the Lord had respect to Abel, and to his offerings.

@c    Had respect. . .That is, shewed his acceptance of his sacrifice (as
@c    coming from a heart full of devotion):  and that, as we may suppose, by
@c    some visible token, such as sending fire from heaven upon his
@c    offerings.

@c    4:5. But to Cain and his offerings he had no respect:  and Cain was
@c    exceeding angry, and his countenance fell.

@c    4:6. And the Lord said to him:  Why art thou angry?  and why is thy
@c    countenance fallen?

@c    4:7. If thou do well, shalt thou not receive?  but if ill, shall not sin
@c    forthwith be present at the door?  but the lust thereof shall be under
@c    thee, and thou shalt have dominion over it.

@c    4:8. And Cain said to Abel his brother:  Let us go forth abroad.  And
@c    when they were in the field, Cain rose up against his brother Abel, and
@c    slew him.

@c    4:9. And the Lord said to Cain:  Where is thy brother Abel?  And he
@c    answered:  I know not:  am I my brother's keeper?

@c    4:10. And he said to him:  What hast thou done?  the voice of thy
@c    brother's blood crieth to me from the earth.

@c    4:11. Now therefore cursed shalt thou be upon the earth, which hath
@c    opened her mouth and received the blood of thy brother at thy hand.

@c    4:12. When thou shalt till it, it shall not yield to thee its fruit:  a
@c    fugitive and a vagabond shalt thou be upon the earth.

@c    4:13. And Cain said to the Lord:  My iniquity is greater than that I may
@c    deserve pardon.

@c    4:14. Behold thou dost cast me out this day from the face of the earth,
@c    and from thy face I shall be hid, and I shall be a vagabond and a
@c    fugitive on the earth:  every one therefore that findeth me, shall kill
@c    me.

@c    Every one that findeth me shall kill me. . .His guilty conscience made
@c    him fear his own brothers and nephews; of whom, by this time, there
@c    might be a good number upon the earth; which had now endured near 130
@c    years; as may be gathered from Gen. 5.3, compared with chap. 4.25,
@c    though in the compendious account given in the scriptures, only Cain
@c    and Abel are mentioned.

@c    4:15. And the Lord said to him:  No, it shall not so be:  but whosoever
@c    shall kill Cain, shall be punished sevenfold.  And the Lord set a mark
@c    upon Cain, that whosoever found him should not kill him.

@c    Set a mark, etc. . .The more common opinion of the interpreters of holy
@c    writ supposes this mark to have been a trembling of the body; or a
@c    horror and consternation in his countenance.

@c    4:16. And Cain went out from the face of the Lord, and dwelt as a
@c    fugitive on the earth at the east side of Eden.

@c    4:17. And Cain knew his wife, and she conceived, and brought forth
@c    Henoch:  and he built a city, and called the name thereof by the name of
@c    his son Henoch.

@c    His wife. . .She was a daughter of Adam, and Cain's own sister; God
@c    dispensing with such marriages in the beginning of the world, as
@c    mankind could not otherwise be propagated.  He built a city, viz. . .In
@c    process of time, when his race was multiplied, so as to be numerous
@c    enough to people it.  For in the many hundred years he lived, his race
@c    might be multiplied even to millions.

@c    4:18. And Henoch begot Irad, and Irad begot Maviael, and Maviael begot
@c    Mathusael, and Mathusael begot Lamech,

@c    4:19. Who took two wives:  the name of the one was Ada, and the name of
@c    the other Sella.

@c    4:20. And Ada brought forth Jabel:  who was the father of such as dwell
@c    in tents, and of herdsmen.

@c    4:21. And his brother's name was Jubal:  he was the father of them that
@c    play upon the harp and the organs.

@c    4:22. Sella also brought forth Tubalcain, who was a hammerer and
@c    artificer in every work of brass and iron.  And the sister of Tubalcain
@c    was Noema.

@c    4:23. And Lamech said to his wives Ada and Sella:  Hear my voice, ye
@c    wives of Lamech, hearken to my speech:  for I have slain a man to the
@c    wounding of myself, and a stripling to my own bruising.

@c    I have slain a man, etc. . .It is the tradition of the Hebrews, that
@c    Lamech in hunting slew Cain, mistaking him for a wild beast; and that
@c    having discovered what he had done, he beat so unmercifully the youth,
@c    by whom he was led into that mistake, that he died of the blows.

@c    4:24. Sevenfold vengeance shall be taken for Cain:  but for Lamech
@c    seventy times sevenfold.

@c    4:25. Adam also knew his wife again:  and she brought forth a son, and
@c    called his name Seth, saying:  God hath given me another seed for Abel,
@c    whom Cain slew.

@c    4:26. But to Seth also was born a son, whom he called Enos:  this man
@c    began to call upon the name of the Lord.

@c    Began to call upon, etc. . .Not that Adam and Seth had not called upon
@c    God, before the birth of Enos; but that Enos used more solemnity in the
@c    worship and invocation of God.



@c    Genesis Chapter 5


@c    The genealogy, age, and death of the Patriarchs, from Adam to Noe.  The
@c    translation of Henoch.

@c    5:1. This is the book of the generation of Adam.  In the day that God
@c    created man, he made him to the likeness of God.

@c    5:2. He created them male and female; and blessed them:  and called
@c    their name Adam, in the day when they were created.

@c    5:3. And Adam lived a hundred and thirty years, and begot a son to his
@c    own image and likeness, and called his name Seth.

@c    5:4. And the days of Adam, after he begot Seth, were eight hundred
@c    years:  and he begot sons and daughters.

@c    5:5. And all the time that Adam lived, came to nine hundred and thirty
@c    years, and he died.

@c    5:6. Seth also lived a hundred and five years, and begot Enos.

@c    5:7. And Seth lived after he begot Enos, eight hundred and seven years,
@c    and begot sons and daughters.

@c    5:8. And all the days of Seth were nine hundred and twelve years, and
@c    he died.

@c    5:9. And Enos lived ninety years, and begot Cainan.

@c    5:10. After whose birth he lived eight hundred and fifteen years, and
@c    begot sons and daughters.

@c    5:11. And all the days of Enos were nine hundred and five years, and he
@c    died.

@c    5:12. And Cainan lived seventy years, and begot Malaleel.

@c    5:13. And Cainan lived after he begot Malaleel, eight hundred and forty
@c    years, and begot sons and daughters.

@c    5:14. And all the days of Cainan were nine hundred and ten years, and
@c    he died.

@c    5:15. And Malaleel lived sixty-five years and begot Jared.

@c    5:16. And Malaleel lived after he begot Jared, eight hundred and thirty
@c    years, and begot sons and daughters.

@c    5:17. And all the days of Malaleel were eight hundred and ninety-five
@c    years, and he died.

@c    5:18. And Jared lived a hundred and sixty-two years, and begot Henoch.

@c    5:19. And Jared lived after he begot Henoch, eight hundred years, and
@c    begot sons and daughters.

@c    5:20. And all the days of Jared were nine hundred and sixty-two years,
@c    and he died.

@c    5:21. And Henoch lived sixty-five years, and begot Mathusala.

@c    5:22. And Henoch walked with God:  and lived after he begot Mathusala,
@c    three hundred years, and begot sons and daughters.

@c    5:23. And all the days of Henoch were three hundred and sixty-five
@c    years.

@c    5:24. And he walked with God, and was seen no more:  because God took
@c    him.

@c    5:25. And Mathusala lived a hundred and eighty-seven years, and begot
@c    Lamech.

@c    5:26. And Mathlusala lived after he begot Lamech, seven hundred and
@c    eighty-two years, and begot sons and daughters.

@c    5:27. And all the days of Mathusala were nine hundred and sixty-nine
@c    years, and he died.

@c    5:28. And Lamech lived a hundred and eighty-two years, and begot a son.

@c    5:29. And he called his name Noe, saying:  This same shall comfort us
@c    from the works and labours of our hands on the earth, which the Lord
@c    hath cursed.

@c    5:30. And Lamech lived after he begot Noe, five hundred and ninety-five
@c    years, and begot sons and daughters.

@c    5:31. And all the days of Lamech came to seven hundred and
@c    seventy-seven years, and he died.  And Noe, when he was five hundred
@c    years old, begot Sem, Cham, and Japheth.



@c    Genesis Chapter 6


@c    Man's sin is the cause of the deluge.  Noe is commanded to build the
@c    ark.

@c    6:1. And after that men began to be multiplied upon the earth, and
@c    daughters were born to them,

@c    6:2. The sons of God seeing the daughters of men, that they were fair,
@c    took to themselves wives of all which they chose.

@c    The sons of God. . .The descendants of Seth and Enos are here called
@c    sons of God from their religion and piety:  whereas the ungodly race of
@c    Cain, who by their carnal affections lay grovelling upon the earth, are
@c    called the children of men.  The unhappy consequence of the former
@c    marrying with the latter, ought to be a warning to Christians to be
@c    very circumspect in their marriages; and not to suffer themselves to be
@c    determined in their choice by their carnal passion, to the prejudice of
@c    virtue or religion.

@c    6:3. And God said:  My spirit shall not remain in man for ever, because
@c    he is flesh, and his days shall be a hundred and twenty years.

@c    His days shall be, etc. . .The meaning is, that man's days, which before
@c    the flood were usually 900 years, should now be reduced to 120 years.
@c    Or rather, that God would allow men this term of 120 years, for their
@c    repentance and conversion, before he would send the deluge.

@c    6:4. Now giants were upon the earth in those days.  For after the sons
@c    of God went in to the daughters of men, and they brought forth
@c    children, these are the mighty men of old, men of renown.

@c    Giants. . .It is likely the generality of men before the flood were of a
@c    gigantic stature in comparison with what men now are.  But these here
@c    spoken of are called giants, as being not only tall in stature, but
@c    violent and savage in their dispositions, and mere monsters of cruelty
@c    and lust.

@c    6:5. And God seeing that the wickedness of men was great on the earth,
@c    and that all the thought of their heart was bent upon evil at all
@c    times,

@c    6:6. It repented him that he had made man on the earth.  And being
@c    touched inwardly with sorrow of heart,

@c    It repented him, etc. . .God, who is unchangeable, is not capable of
@c    repentance, grief, or any other passion.  But these expressions are used
@c    to declare the enormity of the sins of men, which was so provoking as
@c    to determine their Creator to destroy these his creatures, whom before
@c    he had so much favoured.

@c    6:7. He said:  I will destroy man, whom I have created, from the face of
@c    the earth, from man even to beasts, from the creeping thing even to the
@c    fowls of the air, for it repenteth me that I have made them.

@c    6:8. But Noe found grace before the Lord.

@c    6:9. These are the generations of Noe:  Noe was a just and perfect man
@c    in his generations, he walked with God.

@c    6:10. And he begot three sons, Sem, Cham, and Japheth.

@c    6:11. And the earth was corrupted before God, and was filled with
@c    iniquity.

@c    6:12. And when God had seen that the earth was corrupted (for all flesh
@c    had corrupted its way upon the earth),

@c    6:13. He said to Noe:  The end of all flesh is come before me, the earth
@c    is filled with iniquity through them, and I will destroy them with the
@c    earth.

@c    6:14. Make thee an ark of timber planks:  thou shalt make little rooms
@c    in the ark, and thou shalt pitch it within and without.

@c    6:15. And thus shalt thou make it.  The length of the ark shall be three
@c    hundred cubits:  the breadth of it fifty cubits, and the height of it
@c    thirty cubits.

@c    Three hundred cubits, etc. . .The ark, according to the dimensions here
@c    set down, contained four hundred and fifty thousand square cubits;
@c    which was more than enough to contain all the kinds of living
@c    creatures, with all necessary provisions:  even supposing the cubits
@c    here spoken of to have been only a foot and a half each, which was the
@c    least kind of cubits.

@c    6:16. Thou shalt make a window in the ark, and in a cubit shalt thou
@c    finish the top of it:  and the door of the ark thou shalt set in the
@c    side:  with lower, middle chambers, and third stories shalt thou make
@c    it.

@c    6:17. Behold, I will bring the waters of a great flood upon the earth,
@c    to destroy all flesh, wherein is the breath of life under heaven.  All
@c    things that are in the earth shall be consumed.

@c    6:18. And I will establish my covenant with thee, and thou shalt enter
@c    into the ark, thou and thy sons, and thy wife, and the wives of thy
@c    sons with thee.

@c    6:19. And of every living creature of all flesh, thou shalt bring two
@c    of a sort into the ark, that they may live with thee:  of the male sex,
@c    and the female.

@c    6:20. Of fowls according to their kind, and of beasts in their kind,
@c    and of every thing that creepeth on the earth according to its kind:
@c    two of every sort shall go in with thee, that they may live.

@c    6:21. Thou shalt take unto thee of all food that may be eaten, and thou
@c    shalt lay it up with thee:  and it shall be food for thee and them.

@c    6:22. And Noe did all things which God commanded him.



@c    Genesis Chapter 7


@c    Noe with his family go into the ark.  The deluge overflows the earth.

@c    7:1. And the Lord said to him:  Go in, thou and all thy house, into the
@c    ark:  for thee I have seen just before me in this generation.

@c    7:2. Of all clean beasts take seven and seven, the male and the female.

@c    Of all clean. . .The distinction of clean and unclean beasts appears to
@c    have been made before the law of Moses, which was not promulgated till
@c    the year of the world 2514.

@c    7:3. But of the beasts that are unclean two and two, the male and the
@c    female.  Of the fowls also of the air seven and seven, the male and the
@c    female:  that seed may be saved upon the face of the whole earth.

@c    7:4. For yet a while, and after seven days, I will rain upon the earth
@c    forty days and forty nights:  and I will destroy every substance that I
@c    have made, from the face of the earth.

@c    7:5. And Noe did all things which the Lord had commanded him.

@c    7:6. And he was six hundred years old, when the waters of the flood
@c    overflowed the earth.

@c    7:7. And Noe went in and his sons, his wife and the wives of his sons
@c    with him into the ark, because of the waters of the flood.

@c    7:8. And of beasts clean and unclean, and of fowls, and of every thing
@c    that moveth upon the earth,

@c    7:9. Two and two went in to Noe into the ark, male and female, as the
@c    Lord had commanded Noe.

@c    7:10. And after the seven days were passed, the waters of the flood
@c    overflowed the earth.

@c    7:11. In the six hundredth year of the life of Noe, in the second
@c    month, in the seventeenth day of the month, all the fountains of the
@c    great deep were broken up, and the floodgates of heaven were opened:

@c    7:12. And the rain fell upon the earth forty days and forty nights.

@c    7:13. In the selfsame day Noe, and Sem, and Cham, and Japheth, his
@c    sons:  his wife, and the three wives of his sons with them, went into
@c    the ark.

@c    7:14. They and every beast according to its kind, and all the cattle in
@c    their kind, and every thing that moveth upon the earth, according to
@c    its kind, and every fowl according to its kind, all birds, and all that
@c    fly,

@c    7:15. Went in to Noe into the ark, two and two of all flesh, wherein
@c    was the breath of life.

@c    7:16. And they that went in, went in male and female of all flesh, as
@c    God had commanded him:  and the Lord shut him in on the outside.

@c    7:17. And the flood was forty days upon the earth:  and the waters
@c    increased, and lifted up the ark on high from the earth.

@c    7:18. For they overflowed exceedingly:  and filled all on the face of
@c    the earth:  and the ark was carried upon the waters.

@c    7:19. And the waters prevailed beyond measure upon the earth:  and all
@c    the high mountains under the whole heaven were covered.

@c    7:20. The water was fifteen cubits higher than the mountains which it
@c    covered.

@c    7:21. And all flesh was destroyed that moved upon the earth, both of
@c    fowl and of cattle, and of beasts, and of all creeping things that
@c    creep upon the earth:  and all men.

@c    7:22. And all things wherein there is the breath of life on the earth,
@c    died.

@c    7:23. And he destroyed all the substance that was upon the earth, from
@c    man even to beast, and the creeping things and fowls of the air:  and
@c    they were destroyed from the earth:  and Noe only remained, and they
@c    that were with him in the ark.

@c    7:24. And the waters prevailed upon the earth a hundred and fifty days.



@c    Genesis Chapter 8


@c    The deluge ceaseth.  Noe goeth out of the ark, and offereth a sacrifice.
@c    God's covenant to him.

@c    8:1. And God remembered Noe, and all the living creatures, and all the
@c    cattle which were with him in the ark, and brought a wind upon the
@c    earth, and the waters were abated:

@c    8:2. The fountains also of the deep, and the floodgates of heaven, were
@c    shut up, and the rain from heaven was restrained.

@c    8:3. And the waters returned from off the earth going and coming:  and
@c    they began to be abated after a hundred and fifty days.

@c    8:4. And the ark rested in the seventh month, the seven and twentieth
@c    day of the month, upon the mountains of Armenia.

@c    8:5. And the waters were going and decreasing until the tenth month:
@c    for in the tenth month, the first day of the month, the tops of the
@c    mountains appeared.

@c    8:6. And after that forty days were passed, Noe opening the window of
@c    the ark, which he had made, sent forth a raven:

@c    8:7. Which went forth and did not return, till the waters were dried up
@c    upon the earth.

@c    Did not return. . .The raven did not return into the ark; but (as it may
@c    be gathered from the Hebrew) went to and fro; sometimes going to the
@c    mountains, where it found carcasses to feed on:  and other times
@c    returning, to rest upon the top of the ark.

@c    8:8. He sent forth also a dove after him, to see if the waters had now
@c    ceased upon the face of the earth.

@c    8:9. But she not finding where her foot might rest, returned to him
@c    into the ark:  for the waters were upon the whole earth:  and he put
@c    forth his hand, and caught her, and brought her into the ark.

@c    8:10. And having waited yet seven other days, he again sent forth the
@c    dove out of the ark.

@c    8:11. And she came to him in the evening carrying a bough of an olive
@c    tree, with green leaves, in her mouth.  Noe therefore understood that
@c    the waters were ceased upon the earth.

@c    8:12. And he stayed yet other seven days:  and he sent forth the dove,
@c    which returned not any more unto him.

@c    8:13. Therefore in the six hundredth and first year, the first month,
@c    the first day of the month, the waters were lessened upon the earth,
@c    and Noe opening the covering of the ark, looked, and saw that the face
@c    of the earth was dried.

@c    8:14. In the second month, the seven and twentieth day of the month,
@c    the earth was dried.

@c    8:15. And God spoke to Noe, saying:

@c    8:16. Go out of the ark, thou and thy wife, thy sons and the wives of
@c    thy sons with thee.

@c    8:17. All living things that are with thee of all flesh, as well in
@c    fowls as in beasts, and all creeping things that creep upon the earth,
@c    bring out with thee, and go ye upon the earth:  increase and multiply
@c    upon it.

@c    8:18. So Noe went out, he and his sons:  his wife, and the wives of his
@c    sons with him.

@c    8:19. And all living things, and cattle, and creeping things that creep
@c    upon the earth, according to their kinds went out of the ark.

@c    8:20. And Noe built an altar unto the Lord:  and taking of all cattle
@c    and fowls that were clean, offered holocausts upon the altar.

@c    Holocausts,. . .or whole burnt offerings.  In which the whole victim was
@c    consumed by fire upon God's altar, and no part was reserved for the use
@c    of priest or people.

@c    8:21. And the Lord smelled a sweet savour, and said:  I will no more
@c    curse the earth for the sake of man:  for the imagination and thought of
@c    man's heart are prone to evil from his youth:  therefore I will no more
@c    destroy every living soul as I have done.

@c    Smelled, etc. . .A figurative expression, denoting that God was well
@c    pleased with the sacrifices which his servant offered.

@c    8:22. All the days of the earth, seedtime and harvest, cold and heat,
@c    summer and winter, night and day, shall not cease.



@c    Genesis Chapter 9


@c    God blesseth Noe:  forbiddeth blood, and promiseth never more to destroy
@c    the world by water.  The blessing of Sem and Japheth.

@c    9:1. And God blessed Noe and his sons.  And he said to them:  Increase,
@c    and multiply, and fill the earth.

@c    9:2. And let the fear and dread of you be upon all the beasts of the
@c    earth, and upon all the fowls of the air, and all that move upon the
@c    earth:  all the fishes of the sea are delivered into your hand.

@c    9:3. And every thing that moveth, and liveth shall be meat for you:
@c    even as the green herbs have I delivered them all to you:

@c    9:4. Saving that flesh with blood you shall not eat.

@c    9:5. For I will require the blood of your lives at the hand of every
@c    beast, and at the hand of man, at the hand of every man, and of his
@c    brother, will I require the life of man.

@c    9:6. Whosoever shall shed man's blood, his blood shall be shed:  for man
@c    was made to the image of God.

@c    9:7. But increase you and multiply, and go upon the earth and fill it.

@c    9:8. Thus also said God to Noe, and to his sons with him:

@c    9:9. Behold I will establish my covenant with you, and with your seed
@c    after you:

@c    9:10. And with every living soul that is with you, as well in all
@c    birds, as in cattle and beasts of the earth, that are come forth out of
@c    the ark, and in all the beasts of the earth.

@c    9:11. I will establish my covenant with you, and all flesh shall be no
@c    more destroyed with the waters of a flood, neither shall there be from
@c    henceforth a flood to waste the earth.

@c    9:12. And God said:  This is the sign of the covenant which I give
@c    between me and you, and to every living soul that is with you, for
@c    perpetual generations.

@c    9:13. I will set my bow in the clouds, and it shall be the sign of a
@c    covenant between me and between the earth.

@c    9:14. And when I shall cover the sky with clouds, my bow shall appear
@c    in the clouds:

@c    9:15. And I will remember my covenant with you, and with every living
@c    soul that beareth flesh:  and there shall no more be waters of a flood
@c    to destroy all flesh.

@c    9:16. And the bow shall be in the clouds, and I shall see it, and shall
@c    remember the everlasting covenant, that was made between God and every
@c    living soul of all flesh which is upon the earth.

@c    9:17. And God said to Noe:  This shall be the sign of the covenant,
@c    which I have established, between me and all flesh upon the earth.

@c    9:18. And the sons of Noe, who came out of the ark, were Sem, Cham, and
@c    Japheth:  and Cham is the father of Chanaan.

@c    9:19. These three are the sons of Noe:  and from these was all mankind
@c    spread over the whole earth.

@c    9:20. And Noe a husbandman began to till the ground, and planted a
@c    vineyard.

@c    9:21. And drinking of the wine was made drunk, and was uncovered in his
@c    tent.

@c    Drunk. . .Noe by the judgment of the fathers was not guilty of sin, in
@c    being overcome by wine:  because he knew not the strength of it.

@c    9:22. Which when Cham the father of Chanaan had seen, to wit, that his
@c    father's nakedness was uncovered, he told it to his two brethren
@c    without.

@c    9:23. But Sem and Japheth put a cloak upon their shoulders, and going
@c    backward, covered the nakedness of their father:  and their faces were
@c    turned away, and they saw not their father's nakedness.

@c    Covered the nakedness. . .Thus, as St. Gregory takes notice L. 35;
@c    Moral. c. 22, we ought to cover the nakedness, that is, the sins, of
@c    our spiritual parents and superiors.

@c    9:24. And Noe awaking from the wine, when he had learned what his
@c    younger son had done to him,

@c    9:25. He said:  Cursed be Chanaan, a servant of servants shall he be
@c    unto his brethren.

@c    Cursed be Chanaan. . .The curses, as well as the blessings, of the
@c    patriarchs, were prophetical:  And this in particular is here recorded
@c    by Moses, for the children of Israel, who were to possess the land of
@c    Chanaan.  But why should Chanaan be cursed for his father's faults?  The
@c    Hebrews answer, that he being then a boy, was the first that saw his
@c    grandfather's nakedness, and told his father Cham of it; and joined
@c    with him in laughing at it:  which drew upon him, rather than upon the
@c    rest of the children of Cham, this prophetical curse.

@c    9:26. And he said:  Blessed be the Lord God of Sem, be Chanaan his
@c    servant.

@c    9:27. May God enlarge Japheth, and may he dwell in the tents of Sem,
@c    and Chanaan be his servant.

@c    9:28. And Noe lived after the flood three hundred and fifty years.

@c    9:29. And all his days were in the whole nine hundred and fifty years:
@c    and he died.



@c    Genesis Chapter 10


@c    The genealogy of the children of Noe, by whom the world was peopled
@c    after the flood.

@c    10:1. These are the generations of the sons of Noe:  Sem, Cham, and
@c    Japheth:  and unto them sons were born after the flood.

@c    10:2. The sons of Japheth:  Gomer, and Magog, and Madai, and Javan, and
@c    Thubal, and Mosoch, and Thiras.

@c    10:3. And the sons of Gomer:  Ascenez and Riphath and Thogorma.

@c    10:4. And the sons of Javan:  Elisa and Tharsis, Cetthim and Dodanim.

@c    10:5. By these were divided the islands of the Gentiles in their lands,
@c    every one according to his tongue and their families in their nations.

@c    The islands. . .So the Hebrews called all the remote countries, to which
@c    they went by ships from Judea, to Greece, Italy, Spain, etc.

@c    10:6. And the Sons of Cham:  Chus, and Mesram, and Phuth, and Chanaan.

@c    10:7. And the sons of Chus:  Saba, and Hevila, and Sabatha, and Regma,
@c    and Sabatacha.  The sons of Regma:  Saba, and Dadan.

@c    10:8. Now Chus begot Nemrod:  he began to be mighty on the earth.

@c    10:9. And he was a stout hunter before the Lord.  Hence came a proverb:
@c    Even as Nemrod the stout hunter before the Lord.

@c    A stout hunter. . .Not of beasts but of men:  whom by violence and
@c    tyranny he brought under his dominion.  And such he was, not only in the
@c    opinion of men, but before the Lord, that is, in his sight who cannot
@c    be deceived.

@c    10:10. And the beginning of his kingdom was Babylon, and Arach, and
@c    Achad, and Chalanne in the land of Sennaar.

@c    10:11. Out of that land came forth Assur, and built Ninive, and the
@c    streets of the city, and Chale.

@c    10:12. Resen also between Ninive and Chale:  this is the great city.

@c    10:13. And Mesraim begot Ludim, and Anamim and Laabim, Nephthuim.

@c    10:14. And Phetrusim, and Chasluim; of whom came forth the Philistines,
@c    and the Capthorim.

@c    10:15. And Chanaan begot Sidon his firstborn, the Hethite,

@c    10:16. And the Jebusite, and the Amorrhite, and the Gergesite.

@c    10:17. The Hevite and Aracite:  the Sinite,

@c    10:18. And the Aradian, the Samarite, and the Hamathite:  and afterwards
@c    the families of the Chanaanites were spread abroad.

@c    10:19. And the limits of Chanaan were from Sidon as one comes to Gerara
@c    even to Gaza, until thou enter Sodom and Gomorrha, and Adama, and
@c    Seboim even to Lesa.

@c    10:20. These are the children of Cham in their kindreds and tongues,
@c    and generations, and lands, and nations.

@c    10:21. Of Sem also the father of all the children of Heber, the elder
@c    brother of Japheth, sons were born.

@c    10:22. The sons of Sem:  Elam and Assur, and Arphaxad, and Lud, and
@c    Aram.

@c    10:23. The sons of Aram:  Us, and Hull, and Gether; and Mes.

@c    10:24. But Arphaxad begot Sale, of whom was born Heber.

@c    10:25. And to Heber were born two sons:  the name of the one was Phaleg,
@c    because in his days was the earth divided:  and his brother's name
@c    Jectan.

@c    10:26. Which Jectan begot Elmodad, and Saleph, and Asarmoth, Jare,

@c    10:27. And Aduram, and Uzal, and Decla,

@c    10:28. And Ebal, and Abimael, Saba,

@c    10:29. And Ophir, and Hevila, and Jobab.  All these were the sons of
@c    Jectan.

@c    10:30. And their dwelling was from Messa as we go on as far as Sephar,
@c    a mountain in the east.

@c    10:31. These are the children of Sem according to their kindreds and
@c    tongues, and countries in their nations.

@c    10:32. These are the families of Noe, according to their people and
@c    nations.  By these were the nations divided on the earth after the
@c    flood.



@c    Genesis Chapter 11


@c    The tower of Babel.  The confusion of tongues.  The genealogy of Sem down
@c    to Abram.

@c    11:1. And the earth was of one tongue, and of the same speech.

@c    11:2. And when they removed from the east, they found a plain in the
@c    land of Sennaar, and dwelt in it.

@c    11:3. And each one said to his neighbour:  Come let us make brick, and
@c    bake them with fire.  And they had brick instead of stones, and slime
@c    instead of mortar:

@c    11:4. And they said:  Come, let us make a city and a tower, the top
@c    whereof may reach to heaven; and let us make our name famous before we
@c    be scattered abroad into all lands.

@c    11:5. And the Lord came down to see the city and the tower, which the
@c    children of Adam were building.

@c    11:6. And he said:  Behold, it is one people, and all have one tongue:
@c    and they have begun to do this, neither will they leave off from their
@c    designs, till they accomplish them in deed.

@c    11:7. Come ye, therefore, let us go down, and there confound their
@c    tongue, that they may not understand one another's speech.

@c    11:8. And so the Lord scattered them from that place into all lands,
@c    and they ceased to build the city.

@c    11:9. And therefore the name thereof was called Babel, because there
@c    the language of the whole earth was confounded:  and from thence the
@c    Lord scattered them abroad upon the face of all countries.

@c    Babel. . .That is, confusion.

@c    11:10. These are the generations of Sem:  Sem was a hundred years old
@c    when he begot Arphaxad, two years after the flood.

@c    11:11. And Sem lived after he begot Arphaxad, five hundred years, and
@c    begot sons and daughters.

@c    11:12. And Arphaxad lived thirty-five years, and begot Sale.

@c    11:13. And Arphaxad lived after he begot Sale, three hundred and three
@c    years, and begot sons and daughters.

@c    11:14. Sale also lived thirty years, and begot Heber.

@c    11:15. And Sale lived after he begot Heber, four hundred and three
@c    years:  and begot sons and daughters.

@c    11:16. And Heber lived thirty-four years, and begot Phaleg.

@c    11:17. And Heber lived after he begot Phaleg, four hundred and thirty
@c    years:  and begot sons and daughters.

@c    11:18. Phaleg also lived thirty years, and begot Reu.

@c    11:19. And Phaleg lived after he begot Reu, two hundred and nine years,
@c    and begot sons and daughters.

@c    11:20. And Reu lived thirty-two years, and begot Sarug.

@c    11:21. And Reu lived after he begot Sarug, two hundred and seven years,
@c    and begot sons and daughters.

@c    11:22. And Sarug lived thirty years, and begot Nachor.

@c    11:23. And Sarug lived after he begot Nachor, two hundred years, and
@c    begot sons and daughters.

@c    11:24. And Nachor lived nine and twenty years, and begot Thare.

@c    11:25. And Nachor lived after he begot Thare, a hundred and nineteen
@c    years, and begot sons and daughters.

@c    11:26. And Thare lived seventy years, and begot Abram, and Nachor, and
@c    Aran.

@c    11:27. And these are the generations of Thare:  Thare begot Abram,
@c    Nachor, and Aran.  And Aran begot Lot.

@c    11:28. And Aran died before Thare his father, in the land of his
@c    nativity in Ur of the Chaldees.

@c    11:29. And Abram and Nachor married wives:  the name of Abram's wife was
@c    Sarai:  and the name of Nachor's wife, Melcha, the daughter of Aran,
@c    father of Melcha and father of Jescha.

@c    11:30. And Sarai was barren, and had no children.

@c    11:31. And Thare took Abram his son, and Lot the son of Aran, his son's
@c    son, and Sarai his daughter in law, the wife of Abram his son, and
@c    brought them out of Ur of the Chaldees, to go into the land of Chanaan:
@c    and they came as far as Haran, and dwelt there.

@c    11:32. And the days of Thare were two hundred and five years, and he
@c    died in Haran.



@c    Genesis Chapter 12


@c    The call of Abram, and the promise made to him.  He sojourneth in
@c    Chanaan, and then by occasion of a famine, goeth down to Egypt.

@c    12:1. And the Lord said to Abram:  Go forth out of thy country, and from
@c    thy kindred, and out of thy father's house, and come into the land
@c    which I shall shew thee.

@c    12:2. And I will make of thee a great nation, and I will bless thee,
@c    and magnify thy name, and thou shalt be blessed.

@c    12:3. I will bless them that bless thee, and curse them that curse
@c    thee, and IN THEE shall all the kindreds of the earth be blessed.

@c    12:4. So Abram went out as the Lord had commanded him, and Lot went
@c    with him:  Abram was seventy-five years old when he went forth from
@c    Haran.

@c    12:5. And he took Sarai his wife, and Lot his brother's son, and all
@c    the substance which they had gathered, and the souls which they had
@c    gotten in Haran:  and they went out to go into the land of Chanaan.  And
@c    when they were come into it,

@c    12:6. Abram passed through the country unto the place of Sichem, as far
@c    as the noble vale:  now the Chanaanite was at that time in the land.

@c    12:7. And the Lord appeared to Abram, and said to him:  To thy seed will
@c    I give this land.  And he built there an altar to the Lord, who had
@c    appeared to him.

@c    12:8. And passing on from thence to a mountain, that was on the east
@c    side of Bethel, he there pitched his tent, having Bethel on the west,
@c    and Hai on the east:  he built there also an altar to the Lord, and
@c    called upon his name.

@c    12:9. And Abram went forward, going and proceeding on to the south.

@c    12:10. And there came a famine in the country:  and Abram went down into
@c    Egypt, to sojourn there:  for the famine was very grievous in the land.

@c    12:11. And when he was near to enter into Egypt, he said to Sarai his
@c    wife:  I know that thou art a beautiful woman:

@c    12:12. And that when the Egyptians shall see thee, they will say:  She
@c    is his wife:  and they will kill me, and keep thee.

@c    12:13. Say, therefore, I pray thee, that thou art my sister:  that I may
@c    be well used for thee, and that my soul may live for thy sake.

@c    My sister. . .This was no lie; because she was his niece, being daughter
@c    to his brother Aran, and therefore, in the style of the Hebrews, she
@c    might truly be called his sister, as Lot is called Abram's brother,
@c    Gen. 14.14.  See Gen. 20.12.

@c    12:14. And when Abram was come into Egypt, the Egyptians saw the woman
@c    that she was very beautiful.

@c    12:15. And the princes told Pharao, and praised her before him:  and the
@c    woman was taken into the house of Pharao.

@c    12:16. And they used Abram well for her sake.  And he had sheep and oxen
@c    and he asses, and men servants, and maid servants, and she asses, and
@c    camels.

@c    12:17. But the Lord scourged Pharao and his house with most grievous
@c    stripes for Sarai, Abram's wife.

@c    12:18. And Pharao called Abram, and said to him:  What is this that thou
@c    hast done to me?  Why didst thou not tell me that she was thy wife?

@c    12:19. For what cause didst thou say, she was thy sister, that I might
@c    take her to my wife?  Now therefore there is thy wife, take her, and go
@c    thy way.

@c    12:20. And Pharao gave his men orders concerning Abram:  and they led
@c    him away and his wife, and all that he had.



@c    Genesis Chapter 13


@c    Abram and Lot part from each other.  God's promise to Abram.

@c    13:1. And Abram went up out of Egypt, he and his wife, and all that he
@c    had, and Lot with him into the south.

@c    13:2. And he was very rich in possession of gold and silver.

@c    13:3. And he returned by the way, that he came, from the south to
@c    Bethel, to the place where before he had pitched his tent between
@c    Bethel and Hai,

@c    13:4. In the place of the altar which he had made before, and there he
@c    called upon the name of the Lord.

@c    13:5. But Lot also, who was with Abram, had flocks of sheep, and herds
@c    of beasts, and tents.

@c    13:6. Neither was the land able to bear them, that they might dwell
@c    together:  for their substance was great, and they could not dwell
@c    together.

@c    13:7. Whereupon also there arose a strife between the herdsmen of Abram
@c    and of Lot.  And at that time the Chanaanite and the Pherezite dwelled
@c    in that country.

@c    13:8. Abram therefore said to Lot:  Let there be no quarrel, I beseech
@c    thee, between me and thee, and between my herdsmen and thy herdsmen:
@c    for we are brethren.

@c    13:9. Behold the whole land is before thee:  depart from me, I pray
@c    thee:  if thou wilt go to the left hand, I will take the right:  if thou
@c    choose the right hand, I will pass to the left.

@c    13:10. And Lot lifting up his eyes, saw all the country about the
@c    Jordan, which was watered throughout, before the Lord destroyed Sodom
